<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Conversation Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Play a scripted exchange between two Event Point participants, usually the player and an NPC, then allow later mission logic to continue after the conversation is finished.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Conversation Event Points Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A <Bold>Conversation</Bold> Event Point plays a dialogue exchange between two participants.
        It is different from a Message Event Point because it is usually a back-and-forth sequence
        rather than a single radio line or prompt. Existing missions use conversations for story
        scenes, objective handoffs, character introductions, warnings, interrogations, and short
        exchanges that lead into the next mission step.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        A conversation usually has three parts: the Event Point that starts it, the two participant
        Event Point references stored by the Conversation itself, and any follow-up Event Points
        that wait for the conversation using <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Use Conversation when the player should hear an exchange between characters. Use Message when the player only needs one short line of instruction or feedback.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Conversation uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point
        type, letter group, colour, position, facing direction, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The index number and Event Point type are automatic. Letter group and colour are useful for
        keeping the conversation, the characters involved, and any follow-up Event Points together
        in the editor and debug tools.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The position matters when the conversation uses a spatial trigger such as
        <Bold>Radius</Bold>, <Bold>Cuboid</Bold>, or <Bold>Player Uses Radius</Bold>. Place the
        Conversation Event Point where the player should enter, interact, or pass through to start
        the exchange.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Trigger settings decide when the conversation starts. Conversations commonly begin after
        player interaction, a previous objective dependency, a person being seen, an area check, or
        a previous conversation ending.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Conversation-Specific Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Conversation has type-specific settings that define who is speaking and how the conversation
        is presented. These are separate from the common Event Point properties.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Person 1 Event Point</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The first participant in the conversation. This is usually the player, a mission NPC, or the
        character who starts the exchange. Existing summaries often appear as two references, such
        as <Bold>EP 1 ↔ EP 96</Bold>, which means the conversation is between those two Event Points.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Person 2 Event Point</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The second participant in the conversation. This should point at the other character or
        speaker involved. If both participant references point at the same Event Point, the
        conversation is usually functioning more like a self-report or radio-style monologue.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Conversation Text</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Conversation text is stored as a sequence of lines. In the exported data, each spoken line is
        separated by a vertical bar character. When authoring, think of each segment as the next
        line in the exchange rather than one continuous paragraph.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Grab Camera</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Some conversations set <Bold>Grab Camera</Bold>. Use this when the conversation should take
        control of the camera or feel more like a directed scene. Leave it off for simpler exchanges
        where the player can keep normal view control.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Set the two participant Event Points first. Most conversation mistakes come from the trigger being correct but the participant references pointing at the wrong people.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        How Missions Trigger Conversations
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Conversation Event Points are usually started by interaction, previous mission logic, line
        of sight, or entering an area. The most useful trigger patterns are:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Person Used</Bold> - starts a conversation when the player uses or talks to a person.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> - starts a conversation after another Event Point has fired.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Boolean AND</Bold> - starts a conversation after two previous conditions are true.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Person Seen</Bold> - starts a conversation when one person sees another.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Radius / Cuboid</Bold> - starts a conversation when the player enters a round or rectangular area.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> - starts a follow-up conversation after another conversation finishes.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Specific Item Held</Bold> - starts a conversation after the player obtains or carries the required item.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical trigger detail:</Run>
                <Run> Trigger the Conversation Event Point itself. Follow-up Event Points should use Conversation Over and reference the Conversation Event Point that must finish.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Conversation Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Player Talks To A Person</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Person Used</Bold> when the conversation should start because the player talks to
        or uses a person. This is the normal pattern for optional dialogue, objective handoffs, and
        character interaction.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Bankbomb1.ucm</Bold>, Conversation <Bold>15</Bold> is between Event Point
        <Bold>3</Bold> and Event Point <Bold>1</Bold>. It uses <Bold>Person Used</Bold> with
        <Bold>Active While</Bold>, so the exchange starts from direct interaction with the person.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create the person/NPC first, create the Conversation, set Person 1 and Person 2 to the
        correct participants, then set the trigger to <Bold>Person Used</Bold>. Use
        <Bold>Active While</Bold> only when the conversation should remain tied to the interaction
        state.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Conversation After An Objective</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> when the conversation should begin after another Event Point has
        completed. This is useful for story beats after a pickup, rescue, arrest, camera scene,
        counter, or other objective stage.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Acarry.ucm</Bold>, Conversation <Bold>97</Bold> is between Event Point
        <Bold>1</Bold> and Event Point <Bold>96</Bold>. It depends on Event Point <Bold>128</Bold>,
        so the conversation waits for an earlier mission step before it plays.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>Dependency</Bold> and set <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the
        Event Point that must happen first. Use <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> on later Event Points
        if the mission must wait until the dialogue has actually finished.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Conversation When Someone Is Seen</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Person Seen</Bold> when the conversation should start because one character sees
        another. This pattern is useful for confrontations, warnings, enemy callouts, civilians
        reacting to the player, or story characters noticing each other.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>bball2.ucm</Bold>, Conversation <Bold>337</Bold> is between Event Point
        <Bold>325</Bold> and Event Point <Bold>1</Bold>. The trigger is <Bold>Person Seen</Bold>,
        using Event Point <Bold>325</Bold> as the person being seen and Event Point <Bold>1</Bold>
        as the observer.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Area-Based Conversations</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Radius</Bold> or <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> when dialogue should begin because the player
        enters a particular location. Cuboid is better for rectangular rooms, alleys, or large areas;
        Radius is better for a local circular trigger point.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed Radius example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>e3.ucm</Bold>, Conversation <Bold>49</Bold> uses <Bold>Radius</Bold> with radius
        <Bold>160</Bold>. The conversation is between Event Point <Bold>48</Bold> and Event Point
        <Bold>2</Bold>, so it starts when the player reaches the local conversation area.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed Cuboid example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Acarry.ucm</Bold>, Conversation <Bold>330</Bold> uses <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> with
        decoded half-sizes of <Bold>284</Bold> by <Bold>296</Bold>. This creates a rectangular
        trigger area for the exchange between Event Point <Bold>328</Bold> and Event Point
        <Bold>329</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Conversation Chains</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> when a second conversation or another Event Point should
        wait until a previous conversation has ended. This is the right way to build multi-stage
        dialogue scenes.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>botanicc.ucm</Bold>, Conversation <Bold>120</Bold> is triggered by
        <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> and references Event Point <Bold>118</Bold>. This creates a
        follow-up exchange after the earlier conversation has completed.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Item-Gated Conversations</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Specific Item Held</Bold> when the conversation should occur only after the player
        has a particular item. This is useful for evidence, keys, tapes, notes, or other mission
        objects that unlock new dialogue.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>MIB.ucm</Bold>, Conversation <Bold>291</Bold> is triggered by
        <Bold>Specific Item Held</Bold> and references Event Point <Bold>289</Bold>. The conversation
        functions as a report after the player obtains the relevant item.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Conversation Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Decide who the two conversation participants are.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create or identify the Event Points for those participants.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Conversation</Bold> Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Person 1 Event Point</Bold> and <Bold>Person 2 Event Point</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Enter the conversation text as separate lines in the intended speaking order.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Enable <Bold>Grab Camera</Bold> only if the conversation should take over the view.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the trigger that starts the conversation: Person Used, Dependency, Radius, Cuboid, Person Seen, Conversation Over, or Specific Item Held.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create follow-up Event Points with <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> if later mission logic must wait for the dialogue to finish.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save and test the full sequence in order, including repeated interaction attempts.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run>
                <Run> Person 1 and Person 2 are correct, the trigger starts the conversation at the right time, Grab Camera is intentional, and any follow-up logic uses Conversation Over rather than assuming the conversation has finished immediately.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
